 usual Welsh form is <i>Tewdwr</i>.","Romanian and Croatian: from the personal name <i>Tudor</i>, a variant of <i>Teodor</i> (see   Theodore  ).","History: The Tudor royal family, English sovereigns from the accession of Henry VII in 1485 to the death of Elizabeth I in 1603, were of Welsh origin, being descended from Owain ap Maredudd ap Tudur, who held lands at Penmynydd in Anglesey."]}]},{"name":"Goronwy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name of uncertain derivation, borne in the <i>Mabinogi</i> by  Goronwy the Staunch , Lord of Penllyn. He became the lover of the flower-maiden Blodeuedd and murdered her husband  Lleu Llaw Gyffes , but Lleu was later restored to life and definitively dispatched Goronwy."],"variants":[{"name":"Gronw","meanings":["Variant of   Goronwy ."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Goronwy ap Tudur was born in 1360, in Penmynydd, Anglesey, Wales, his father, Gronwy \"Fychan\" Ap Gronwy, was 26 and his mother, Margred Marged ferch Thomas, was 30. He died on 23 March 1383, at the age of 23, and was buried in Gaerwen, Anglesey, Wales."},"et":{"1360–23 March 1383":"1360–23. märts 1383","1360–1383":"1360–1383","1365–1406":"1365–1406","1365–1412":"1365–1412","1367–1413":"1367–1413","1370–1406":"1370–1406","1371–1413":"1371–1413","–1413":"–1413","1359–Female":"1359–Surnud","1364–Female":"1364–Surnud","1382–Female":"1382–Surnud","–1400":"–1400","1334–1367":"1334–1367","1330–1388":"1330–1388","1330":"1330","1383":"1383","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1371":"1371","19 September 1367":"19. september 1367","1370":"1370","23 March 1383":"23. märts 1383","1359":"1359","1413":"1413","1412":"1412","1334":"1334","1400":"1400","1367":"1367","1388":"1388","1365":"1365","1364":"1364","before 1382":"enne 1382","1406":"1406","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Penmynydd, Anglesey, Wales":"Penmynydd, Anglesey, Wales","Gaerwen, Anglesey, Wales":"Gaer